ntire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"d79106a5-a980-46f7-b56d-1c2701ed4a9d\",\"version\":\"2.1.72\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/add-support-for-different-remote-for-checkpoints\",\"slug\":\"refactored-shimmying-meteor\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_015mmXnqrey2c57tRzvUFZ8p\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1015,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":44344,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1015},\"output_tokens\":9,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYwGYRLsQBQjPCmeEhZ3T\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"34ca7880-887b-4887-ba3c-5e23b9cecddd\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-11T12:10:45.420Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"34ca7880-887b-4887-ba3c-5e23b9cecddd\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"d79106a5-a980-46f7-b56d-1c2701ed4a9d\",\"version\":\"2.1.72\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/add-support-for-different-remote-for-checkpoints\",\"slug\":\"refactored-shimmying-meteor\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_015mmXnqrey2c57tRzvUFZ8p\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here's how I'd put it together:\\n\\n### Settings structure\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"strategy_options\\\": {\\n    \\\"checkpoint_remote\\\": {\\n      \\\"provider\\\": \\\"github\\\",\\n      \\\"repo\\\": \\\"org/checkpoints-repo\\\"\\n    }\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nExtensible — future providers (`\\\"gitlab\\\"`, `\\\"bitbucket\\\"`, a self-hosted Entire backend, etc.) slot in by adding a new provider value. The `repo` field is always `owner/name`.\\n\\n### URL derivation at runtime\\n\\nInstead of storing a URL, derive it from origin's protocol:\\n\\n1. Read origin's URL (`git remote get-url origin`)\\n2. Parse protocol:\\n   - `git@github.com:...` → SSH → `git@github.com:{repo}.git`\\n   - `https://github.com/...` → HTTPS → `https://github.com/{repo}.git`\\n3. This automatically matches whatever auth the user already has working\\n\\n### Fork detection\\n\\nBefore creating/using the remote:\\n\\n1. Parse origin URL → extract owner (e.g. `fork-user` from `git@github.com:fork-user/original-repo.git`)\\n2. Compare to checkpoint_remote repo owner (`org` from `org/checkpoints-repo`)\\n3. If they differ → skip silently (or with a debug log). The fork can't push to the upstream checkpoint repo anyway.\\n\\n### Remote management rules\\n\\n`entire-checkpoints` is **our** remote — we own it, users shouldn't touch it:\\n\\n- **Doesn't exist** → create it with the derived URL\\n- **Exists, URL matches** → use it\\n- **Exists, URL differs** → update it (setting changed, or user switched SSH↔HTTPS on origin). It's our remote.\\n\\nBut before pushing, check: if `entire/checkpoints/v1` is already being pushed to a remote that's **neither the default nor `entire-checkpoints`** — someone set up a custom remote for this branch manually. Don't override that. In practice this means: in `resolvePushSettings`, if the branch has an explicit push remote configured in git config that isn't origin or `entire-checkpoints`, respect it and skip the checkpoint_remote logic.\\n\\n### Edge case: origin changes protocol\\n\\nUser switches origin from SSH to HTTPS (or vice versa). Next push: we re-derive the checkpoint URL from origin, see it differs from what `entire-checkpoints` currently has, update it. Seamless.\\n\\n### `--checkpoint-remote` flag\\n\\nWould change to something like:\\n\\n```\\nentire enable --checkpoint-remote github:org/checkpoints-repo\\n```\\n\\nwhich parses into the structured `{\\\"provider\\\": \\\"github\\\", \\\"repo\\\": \\\"org/checkpoints-repo\\\"}`.\\n\\n---\\n\\nWant me to start implementing this?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_seq